p align=left class=m><span class=title> Re:  A Sermon</span><hr size=1> This bit of dueling dogmas has been amusing.<br>
<br>
But really, it comes down to the definition of power.  What is power?<br>
<br>
I'm sure you all must agree on the importance of knowledge, however.  All wizards pursue knowledge as a means to power.  Some understand that power is a means to knowledge.  Knowledge is power, and power is knowledge.<br>
<br>
This is where both dogmas fail.<br>
<br>
The followers of Innoruuk will readily admit to oppressing truth and propigating falsehoods, destroying knowledge, when it serves their rhetoric of hate.  Thus Innoruuk stifles the power that presumably would promote his hate.<br>
<br>
And Solusek Ro clearly has no regard for knowledge.  There is some evidence, and reasonable conjecture, that Takish-Hiz had an excellent library.  Whether Solusek's destruction of Takish-Hiz was calculated or a hissy-fit is immaterial, the result was the destruction and loss of all that valuable knowledge.  Is that a proper course of action for one who espouses power?<br>
<br>
Enslaving oneself to these &quot;gods&quot;, or any of the others, is to place blinders on oneself.  I prefer to see.<br>
 <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://home.nycap.rr.com/jdailey1/sigs/eqz.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=eaminwhitefalcon@graffeswizardcompilation>Eamin Whitefalcon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Arcanist<BR>¡Viva la inquisición!</span><br>  Posts: 6646<br> <font color=#ffffff>(4/18/03 7:30 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re:  A Sermon</span><hr size=1> Remember that the destruction of Takish`Hiz did not take place in the place of a single night or any such thing of that sort. It occured over the space of many years - more than enough time for the Elves to cart away their vast libraries, or for the Teir`Dal to sweep in and carry away the volumes.<br>
<br>
And furthermore:  the Great Lord had no need of the knowledge secreted away in the old Elven empire. If it was destroyed it would not have had any effect on His Holy Plans - it was old news. He knew it all. It was useless to Him.<br>
<br>
Also, you base your entire argument on the foolish premise that knowledge necessarily equates power. It does not. In many instances acquiring knowledge will enable one to gain power - but acquiring knowledge is but a means to the end, the end being power (power itself is also a means to gaining itself, as you will remember). Knowledge means nothing independent of power. THAT is the philosophy of Ro, and that is the philosophy of wizardry! <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=eedelia01>Eedelia01</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Visitor</span><br>  Posts: 8<br> <font color=#ffffff>(4/20/03 12:25 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: A Sermon</span><hr size=1> &lt;grins with a hint of antaginization&gt;<br>
<br>
But what about Karana's followers? They are able to perform the same sorts of arcane feats and yet he does not follow the path of neither Innoruk or Solusek Ro! I believe that your 'power in hate' theology is highly mistaken.<br>
<br>
Karana's followers believe in the raw power of storms. Does not the storm call forth the ice which covers the hills of halas? Does not the lightning spring forth fire whence struck upon a brush?<br>
<br>
The power from which we draw comes from the elements that surroudn us. As you'll remember, even the 4 most powerful wizards of their day, trained by Solusek himself no less, fell because they were blinded by their power. If Solusek did in fact teach his followers to reach out with thier hate to summon forth the Power, then he was ultimatly the undoing of his prided students. Fury may fuel our magic but as The 2nd wizard learned when challanging Saither, he let his Fury blind him to his opponents power. It cost him his life.<br>
<br>
I have no use for hate in my magic, it is counterproductive, and Innoruk no doubt knows this. Of course, if he hates all of his followers, why would he not tempt them to give into a force which would ultimatly be their undoing? Solusek may have noticed that Hate would spur the power of magic onward as Innoruk has done but as he was forced to strip the magic from his 4 greatest followers, I am sure he learned the true nature of what the Lord of Hate has been planning.<br>
Long ago he set his evil plan in motion, letting his followers call upon the powers of Hate, knowing that in the end, they would also perish. <br>
<br>
I am part of the few, the proud, the followers of Karana. I cannot use things which would require homage to Solusek Ro, but i have lived without them and quite happily let me assure you. I believe in the power of storms and the wisdom that Karana provides through his teachings, untainted by Hate and unfocused, untrained Fury.<br>
<br>
