<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Remember that the destruction of Takish`Hiz did not take place in the place of a single night or any such thing of that sort. It occured over the space of many years - more than enough time for the Elves to cart away their vast libraries, or for the Teir`Dal to sweep in and carry away the volumes.<br>
<br>
And furthermore: the Great Lord had no need of the knowledge secreted away in the old Elven empire. If it was destroyed it would not have had any effect on His Holy Plans - it was old news. He knew it all. It was useless to Him.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Speculation. I've made an extensive study of the Desert of Ro, and I will tell you conclusively that the assault on Takish`Hiz was meant to utterly consume the entire civilization, particularly the monastic, druidic and arcane orders. <br>
<br>
What means did Solusek Ro use? Necromancers and the undead composed the main assault force and was expressly intended to drive mad those that weren't killed. I think someone knew something about the Flaming One(any and all interpretations of this term are accurate) and his plans...something that he either needed to hide out of Fear or destroy because of Hate. In either case, your Prince of Fire is a puppet.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Knowledge means nothing independent of power. THAT is the philosophy of Ro, and that is the philosophy of wizardry! <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Knowledge is an end. Destruction is an end. Power is a means and ONLY a means. Power without motivation, will and purpose is empty and meaningless. Power is the means by which we acquire knowledge, and that knowledge lends greater power to acquire yet more knowledge.  Of course, you should be careful of what knowledge you acquire...Solusek Ro only likes knowledge that's safe to him. Learn the wrong things and your god will destroy you as he has so many others.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>If Solusek did in fact teach his followers to reach out with thier hate to summon forth the Power, then he was ultimatly the undoing of his prided students. Fury may fuel our magic but as The 2nd wizard learned when challanging Saither, he let his Fury blind him to his opponents power. It cost him his life.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Actually, it was Solusek Ro's punishment of said wizard by stripping him of his power that cost him his life. Plainly there is one set of rules for Solusek(ones that use Hatred as Power) and another set for his followers(Hate is bad, mmkay?). I have personally seen wizards strike blows that would utterly destroy Venril Sathir. Solusek Ro's vindictive act of betrayal is what killed that wizard, and that is because the power Solusek's wizards use IS NOT THEIR OWN. It belongs to him. Seriously, look into a deity who isn't such a micromanager.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I have no use for hate in my magic, it is counterproductive, and Innoruk no doubt knows this. Of course, if he hates all of his followers, why would he not tempt them to give into a force which would ultimatly be their undoing? Solusek may have noticed that Hate would spur the power of magic onward as Innoruk has done but as he was forced to strip the magic from his 4 greatest followers, I am sure he learned the true nature of what the Lord of Hate has been planning.<br>
Long ago he set his evil plan in motion, letting his followers call upon the powers of Hate, knowing that in the end, they would also perish.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
To the best of my knowledge, the four wizards that Solusek stripped were not followers nor users of Hate. I contend, in fact, that if they were practitioners of Hate, their power would have come from deep within themselves from an infinitely replenishable source, in which case Solusek Ro would have had no ability to strip their power. Innoruuk's sole contribution to a wizard is the powerful focus that real Hate represents. He does not hold control over our power.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I am part of the few, the proud, the followers of Karana. I cannot use things which would require homage to Solusek Ro, but i have lived without them and quite happily let me assure you. I believe in the power of storms and the wisdom that Karana provides through his teachings, untainted by Hate and unfocused, untrained Fury.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<br>
Erm...what exactly IS a storm if not unfocused fury? Storms strike and destroy at random. The application of Hate gives fury a purpose. On this, as on one other point, Eamin is correct...Karana is indeed a druid god. The other point you may ask? <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> If you utilize hate effectively in a way that helps you attain power, you have done well. If you utilize hate ineffectively and counterproductively, you shall be culled. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Spoken like a true follower of Innoruuk. I applaud you.<br>
 <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=khaymus>Khaymus</A> at: 4/21/03 12:26:29 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=khaymus>Khaymus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Channeler</span><br>  Posts: 208<br> <font color=#ffffff>(4/21/03 11:31 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: More Concepts for the Hatred Impaired</span><hr size=1> Here are a few more concepts for those who think Innoruuk worship is all about irrational behavior, excessive emotionalism and recklessness. Most of you are already applying these ideas to your everyday lives. I hope to convince at least a few fence sitters to take that plunge and embrace the Lord of Hate.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">Cold Hatred</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--></em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
It is not necessary to burn with emotion to invoke Hatred. In the heat on the moment, mistakes can be made easily, and so it is best to avoid passionate encounters. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>The principle of Cold Hatred teaches us that Hate is best used in a combat setting as a channel for magic rather than as expressed emotionalism.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Hatred is a potent conduit for magical energies but it is vitally important not to lose focus. There will be plenty of time to express your emotions when you're standing on your enemies smoldering corpse.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline"><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Knowledge is Victory</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--><br>
<br>
One of the most important aspects of focused Hate is obsession. Know thine enemy as intimately as possible. Absolutely every living being has weaknesses and strengths, each of which are individually exploitable IF you know the proper methods. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Victory over one's enemies is most consistantly achieved through a careful study of their weaknesses and more careful observation of their strengths.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> These things will better enable you to choose a proper time and venue for confrontation.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">A Season for all Things</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--></em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
This principle of Hatred deals with opportunism. It's actually a corollary of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Knowledge as Victory</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> because it deals with certain knowledge of a moment when an enemy will be particularly vulnerable. The ugly death of a loved one, a specific day or time when a prayer is less likely to be answered, travel through hostile or simply unfamiliar terrain are all open doors for those who know how to exploit them. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Fate hands you opportunity, it is your responsibility to judge the risks ands seize it.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Some opponents can only be overcome by taking advantage of transient weakness.<br>
<br>
I leave you with these things to contemplate. Hatred is not all spittle-flecked madness but is a focused approach to life's challenges when applied properly.<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=vdou>Vdou</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Evoker</span><br>  Posts: 304<br> <font color=#ffffff>(4/21/03 11:42 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: !!!</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I think someone knew something about the Flaming One(any and all interpretations of this term are accurate)...something that he either needed to hide out of Fear or destroy because of Hate. In either case, your Prince of Fire is a puppet.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
First of all, the sexual orientations of the gods are totally irreleveant. Even if Solusek Ro were gay, as you and many others have implied, he would still retain the power to destroy all of Norrath. And as well he should, I am beginning to tire of the current gene pool of Norrath's denizens.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Of course, you should be careful of what knowledge you acquire...Solusek Ro only likes knowledge that's safe to him. Learn the wrong things and your god will destroy you as he has so many others.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Destroy us (his followers)? Truth be told, I would gladly give my life to futher the cause of The Burning Prince. I know that when I die I will ascend to the Plane of Fire as an avatar of Solusek's desiring. This is a far better fate than any I could possibly hold while I occupy the Prime Material Plane.<br>
<br>
Furthermore, the whole purpose of Solusek is power and the destruction of our enemies. Destruction of myself is part and parcel of this dogma.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Innoruuk's sole contribution to a wizard [is] the powerful focus that real Hate represents. He does not hold control over our power.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Hate is an emotion. It is very basic, and very simplistic. Do I hate? Yes. Do I let my Hate consume me? No. Does my hatred for various species or dogmas force me to do things that I would otherwise not do? Not in the least bit. <br>
<br>
I am a child of hate. The blood of hate runs through my veins, this is something I have had to accept over my life. I was cast out of the Church of Innoruuk long ago, and I was taken in by the Temple of Solusek Ro. There is a great difference in practice and not so much in philosophy between the followers of Innoruuk and Solusek Ro.<br>
<br>
Yes hate can afford you great power, but at what price? If you cannot love another and your hate is all consuming, I cannot see having much depth to your soul.<br>
<br>
And I know what you would reply with. Power is all consuming, and it is. Yet the dogma of Solusek Ro allows his followers to make choices and alliances with others that Innoruuk would find reprehensible. Not to mention the torture one would endure within the walls of the Church.<br>
<br>
Hate may focus you somewhat, but it blinds you to other opportunities that might present themselves.<br>
<br>
