Fear is a tool for the weak and stupid. There is no greater weapon in all of the universe than flattery.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I have but one mandate...Spread Hatred.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Spread Hatred? Amusing. How short-sighted and easy a task to accomplish! It is almost pittiful, a task for a young apprentice of the Dead for sure!<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>By his actions, he has embraced Hate already or at least given it a firm, manly handshake.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Perhaps, yet hate is never the motivating factor.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=eaminwhitefalcon@graffeswizardcompilation>Eamin Whitefalcon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Arcanist<BR>¡Viva la inquisición!</span><br>  Posts: 6738<br> <font color=#ffffff>(4/23/03 1:48 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: A Sermon</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
Without knowledge, you will find you have no means to shape your evergrowing power. The three key tenets that go along with Power are Will, Knowledge, and Focus(that being Hate). Power undirected and uncontrolled means nothing.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
If it is required to seek knowledge before you may gain that next bit of power, do so. But never seek knowledge for the sake of seeking knowledge - that is a waste of time. Knowledge that bestows no power is useless. However, power that bestows no knowledge is quite handy.<br>
<br>
And hate is in no way a focus. It is a distraction, and nothing more. The only focus is Ambition.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
I use my power to kill; to gain whatever knowledge I desire, to gather further power, and for the simple pleasure of it. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
So, you admit that you squander your power on meaningless and trivial duties?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
There must be a starting point to everything.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The starting point is irrelevant. It is the result that matters.<br>
<br>
For example, how could I gain knowledge if I did not have the power to get up off my back and read an ancient tome? The chicken and the egg are matters of idle speculation, and nothing more. What matters is the end result:  power. Seeking knowledge without gaining power is a fool's errand - otherwise, would you not be satisfied simply learning to fish? Knowing how to fish is knowledge - but it doesn't convey power. Any increase in power is welcome, but the same is not true for knowledge - some increases in knowledge are utterly useless.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
Of course, Solusek Ro just grants you your power, right? No need for you to &quot;waste time&quot; learning to be independant of the King of Candles, eh? It's all a sham. You aren't gathering power for you...you're gathering it for him...and he can strip you of it at any time of his choosing. Weak.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
So, we see the underlying jealousy of the Innorites, jealousy that spurs them to create conspiracy theories to justify their faith in an impotent and useless ideal.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
Depends. Is he as powerful as you pretend he is? Or is he afraid of FOUR MORTAL MEN?<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
If a fire beetle approached you and began to attack you, would you simply sit there and let it? Or would you slay it promptly?<br>
<br>
Any opposition, no matter if it is a real threat or not, must be crushed.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
To the great harm of hundreds of thousands of beings.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Boo hoo?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
Applying your &quot;objective&quot; standard, Solusek Ro is evil.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
No, because to slay hundreds of thousands of beings wasn't his ultimate goal. It was simply a means to achieve his end - which was to curtail the influence of Tunare, and thus increase his own power. If his goal was to slay hundreds of thousands, he would be evil. But that wasn't his goal, his goal was to gain power - and just because you don't give a shit about what happens to hundreds of thousands of beings doesn't mean you fall on the evil end of the spectrum.<br>
<br>
It is intent that judges good or evil, not results. Innoruuk would have killed these elves simply out of malice. Solusek Ro killed them only to further his own ends. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=khaymus>Khaymus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Channeler</span><br>  Posts: 215<br> <font color=#ffffff>(4/25/03 11:00 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: A Sermon</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Your priorities are out of whack.<br>
<br>
First frogloks, next gnomes.<br>
<br>
Druids &gt; Gnomes &gt; Frogloks<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Ok. But as a great number of druids ARE Halflings, wiping them out would reduce druid numbers by a LOT. First Rivervale, then Surefall.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I enjoy tempting death, and coming face to face with it, yet it does not consume me.<br>
<br>
No I do not fish. Nor do I drink. Any time spent not desetroying or usurping my enemies is wasted.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Tempting fate is what we do. Sometimes you get the bear, sometimes the bear gets you. Then you leave the newbie yard, return later with far greater power and get the bear over and over. And sell his pelts. My point being that death is always with us, whether we are dealing it or being subsumed by it. Hatred is a potent fuel in the blood, driving one past mere survival to total victory. Death has no permanent hold on those who Hate. Ask Mayong Mistmoore about that.<br>
<br>
Since you don't already fish, I would suggest not bothering with it. It's boring. Destroying and usurping our enemies is the primary source of entertainment for a wizard for a reason and nothing adds flavor to the victory like Hatred. I savor the expression on the face of the defeated. The look in a Marr paladin's eyes when his faith cracks like a dry, brittle nutshell...the cringe of the druid being consumed by the fires of the sun...the slowly clouding eyes of the dragon whose millenia long existance just ended by magic his enemies taught me. None of these means anything in a cold, dispassionate murder. Only in Hatred can you truly appreciate the subtleties.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Fear is a tool for the weak and stupid.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Nonsense. Fear as a psychological tool is quite powerful...it can result in your opponent defeating himself if applied properly. Really, ease up on embracing the dogmas of lesser religions.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Spread Hatred? Amusing. How short-sighted and easy a task to accomplish! It is almost pittiful, a task for a young apprentice of the Dead for sure!<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>So, you admit that you squander your power on meaningless and trivial duties?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
True, if by <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Spread Hatred</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> you only see the little hatreds. Wizards hate druids. Little Timmy hates brussel sprouts. My mission is far greater in scope. I aim to see a second Hole in Misty Thicket. I desire a Jappedpine canyon. By my designs, Kelethin will crash from the treetops and Kaladim will swallow the dwarves. Velious will melt and wash away Coldain, Giant and Dragon alike. Kunark will sink under the waves. These are Great Changes, wrought by the True Power of Hatred, not some pissant abstract goal of &quot;power&quot;. It will happen and my hand shall be among many that guide it. I have personally foreseen the sinking of Kunark and so that is where my current efforts are focused. Can you say anything of the sort in terms of your life? Oh, I forgot...Solusek Ro wizards just go through life with &quot;Ur gona give me pwr, plz&quot;, eh?<br>
<br>
<br>
